{"title_page": "Arsen Yegiazarian", "text_new": "{{Infobox chess player\n|name = Arsen Yegiazarian\n|image = Arsen_Yegiazarian_Yerevan_2013.jpg\n|caption = \n|birthname = \u0531\u0580\u057d\u0565\u0576 \u0535\u0572\u056b\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580\u0575\u0561\u0576\n|country = {{ARM}}\n|birth_date = {{Birth date|1970|6|18}}\n|birth_place = [[Yerevan]], [[Armenian SSR]]\n|death_date = {{death date and age|2020|4|20|1970|6|18|df=y}}\n|death_place = \n|title = [[Grandmaster (chess)|Grandmaster]]\n|worldchampion = \n|womensworldchampion = \n|peakrating = 2567 (April 2002)\n|FideID = 13300520\n}}\n'''Arsen Yegiazarian''' ({{lang-hy|\u0531\u0580\u057d\u0565\u0576 \u0535\u0572\u056b\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580\u0575\u0561\u0576}}; 18 June 1970 \u2013 20 April 2020) was an [[Armenia]]n [[chess]] [[Grandmaster (chess)|Grandmaster]] (2000) and FIDE Senior Trainer (2011).\n\n==Career==\nYegiazarian graduated from the [[Armenian State Institute of Physical Culture]] in 1992. He became a Grandmaster in chess in 2000. Yegiazarian had won the Armenian Youth Championship in 1984 and 1988 in the under-18 group and came in third place in at the senior [[Armenian Chess Championship]] in 1998 and 2000. The [[Yerevan]] city chess club, which included Yegiazarian, won the 1995 [[European Chess Club Cup]]. Yegiazarian won the international tournament in [[Tbilisi]] 2001 and came in first place at [[Batumi]] that same year. In 2005, he came in first place at the [[Aeroflot Open]] section of the A2 Tournament.<ref>{{cite web|title=Moscow Aeroflot op-B|url=https://www.365chess.com/tournaments/Moscow_Aeroflot_op-B_2005/33569|publisher=365chess|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> He competed at the [[Chess Olympiad]]s in [[1994 Chess Olympiad|1994]]<ref>{{cite web|title=31st Chess Olympiad: Moscow 1994|url=http://www.olimpbase.org/1994/1994arm.html|publisher=OlimpBase|accessdate=1 June 2013}}</ref> and [[1996 Chess Olympiad|1996]].\n\nYegiazarian was coach of Armenian men national chess team in 1998 and, in 2000, became coach of the Armenian women national team. Since 2002, he has been working at the [[Yerevan Chess House]] as a trainer. Yegiazarian was named a [[FIDE]] Senior Trainer in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yegiazarian, Arsen FIDE Chess Profile - Players Arbiters Trainers|url=https://ratings.fide.com/card.phtml?event=13300520|publisher=FIDE|accessdate=15 November 2017}}</ref> In 2012, he was awarded the title Honored Coach of Armenia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Decrees of the President of RA|url=http://xn--y9aaah2cva0b.xn--y9a3aq/hy/decrees/item/819|publisher=The President of the Republic of Armenia (the official site)|accessdate=1 December 2017}} (in Armenian)</ref> Yegiazarian, who won the Armenian National Chess Championship in 2005, 2006, and 2007 <ref>https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessplayer?pid=49431</ref>, died on April 20, 2020.\n\n==Achievements==\n\n*1984, 1988: Won Armenian Youth Championship (Under-18);\n*1995: Won European Cup being a member of \"Yerevan\" team;\n*1998: Third place at [[Armenian Chess Championship]];{{sfn|\u0549\u0561\u057f\u056b\u0576\u0575\u0561\u0576|1999|p=95}}\n*2000: Third place at [[Armenian Chess Championship]];\n*2001: Won International Tournament in [[Tbilisi]];\n*2001: Second place at International Tournament in [[Batumi]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Batumi op 2001|url=https://www.365chess.com/tournaments/Batumi_op_2001/4111|publisher=365chess|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref>\n*2005: First place at [[Aeroflot Open]] section A2 Tournament;<ref>{{cite web|title=Moscow Aeroflot op-B 2005|url=https://www.365chess.com/tournaments/Moscow_Aeroflot_op-B_2005/33569|publisher=365chess|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref>\n*2005, 2006, 2007: First place at Armenian National Chess Championship. <ref>https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessplayer?pid=49431</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{citation |last=\u0549\u0561\u057f\u056b\u0576\u0575\u0561\u0576 |first=\u054c\u0561\u0586\u0561\u0575\u0565\u056c |year=1999 |title=\u0539\u0561\u0563\u0561\u056f\u056b\u0580\u0576\u0565\u0580\u0568 (1934-1998 \u0569\u0569.) |page=95 |publisher= |language=Armenian |isbn= }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{chessgames player|id=49431}}\n*[http://www.365chess.com/players/Arsen_Yegiazarian Arsen Yegiazarian] chess games at 365Chess.com\n*[http://www.redhotpawn.com/chess/grandmaster-games/index.php?player=Arsen_Yegiazarian&masterplayerid=1263 Grandmaster Games Database - Arsen Yegiazarian]\n*[http://www.olimpbase.org/players/tpltphti.html Olimpbase record] for Arsen Yegiazarian\n*[http://bbs.zixia.net/elite.php?file=%2Fgroups%2FEntertain%2Fchess%2Fsmthjh%2F5%2Fcontest%2F2004%2Ffourcountry%2F00000017.txt Interview with GM Arsen Yegiazarian]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090115021417/http://www.chessacademy.am/index.php?Page=Yerevan&Lang=1 Chess Academy of Armenia]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yegiazarian, Arsen}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Yerevan]]\n[[Category:Armenian State Institute of Physical Culture alumni]]\n[[Category:Chess grandmasters]]\n[[Category:Chess Olympiad competitors]]\n[[Category:Armenian chess players]]\n[[Category:Chess coaches]]\n[[Category:National team coaches]]\n\n\n{{Armenia-chess-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox chess player\n|name = Arsen Yegiazarian\n|image = Arsen_Yegiazarian_Yerevan_2013.jpg\n|caption = \n|birthname = \u0531\u0580\u057d\u0565\u0576 \u0535\u0572\u056b\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580\u0575\u0561\u0576\n|country = {{ARM}}\n|birth_date = {{Birth date|1970|6|18}}\n|birth_place = [[Yerevan]], [[Armenian SSR]]\n|death_date = {{death date and age|2020|4|20|1970|6|18|df=y}}\n|death_place = \n|title = [[Grandmaster (chess)|Grandmaster]]\n|worldchampion = \n|womensworldchampion = \n|peakrating = 2567 (April 2002)\n|FideID = 13300520\n}}\n'''Arsen Yegiazarian''' ({{lang-hy|\u0531\u0580\u057d\u0565\u0576 \u0535\u0572\u056b\u0561\u0566\u0561\u0580\u0575\u0561\u0576}}; 18 June 1970 \u2013 20 April 2020) was an [[Armenia]]n [[chess]] [[Grandmaster (chess)|Grandmaster]] (2000) and FIDE Senior Trainer (2011).\n\n==Career==\nYegiazarian graduated from the [[Armenian State Institute of Physical Culture]] in 1992. He became a Grandmaster in chess in 2000. Yegiazarian had won the Armenian Youth Championship in 1984 and 1988 in the under-18 group and came in third place in at the senior [[Armenian Chess Championship]] in 1998 and 2000. The [[Yerevan]] city chess club, which included Yegiazarian, won the 1995 [[European Chess Club Cup]]. Yegiazarian won the international tournament in [[Tbilisi]] 2001 and came in first place at [[Batumi]] that same year. In 2005, he came in first place at the [[Aeroflot Open]] section of the A2 Tournament.<ref>{{cite web|title=Moscow Aeroflot op-B|url=https://www.365chess.com/tournaments/Moscow_Aeroflot_op-B_2005/33569|publisher=365chess|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe competed at the [[Chess Olympiad]]s in [[1994 Chess Olympiad|1994]]<ref>{{cite web|title=31st Chess Olympiad: Moscow 1994|url=http://www.olimpbase.org/1994/1994arm.html|publisher=OlimpBase|accessdate=1 June 2013}}</ref> and [[1996 Chess Olympiad|1996]].\n\nYegiazarian was coach of Armenian men national chess team in 1998 and, in 2000, became coach of the Armenian women national team. Since 2002, he has been working at the [[Yerevan Chess House]] as a trainer. Yegiazarian was named a [[FIDE]] Senior Trainer in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yegiazarian, Arsen FIDE Chess Profile - Players Arbiters Trainers|url=https://ratings.fide.com/card.phtml?event=13300520|publisher=FIDE|accessdate=15 November 2017}}</ref> In 2012, he was awarded the title Honored Coach of Armenia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Decrees of the President of RA|url=http://xn--y9aaah2cva0b.xn--y9a3aq/hy/decrees/item/819|publisher=The President of the Republic of Armenia (the official site)|accessdate=1 December 2017}} (in Armenian)</ref> Yegiazarian, who won the Armenian National Chess Championship in 2005, 2006, and 2007 <ref>https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessplayer?pid=49431</ref>, died on April 20, 2020.\n\n==Achievements==\n\n*1984, 1988: Won Armenian Youth Championship (Under-18);\n*1995: Won European Cup being a member of \"Yerevan\" team;\n*1998: Third place at [[Armenian Chess Championship]];{{sfn|\u0549\u0561\u057f\u056b\u0576\u0575\u0561\u0576|1999|p=95}}\n*2000: Third place at [[Armenian Chess Championship]];\n*2001: Won International Tournament in [[Tbilisi]];\n*2001: Second place at International Tournament in [[Batumi]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Batumi op 2001|url=https://www.365chess.com/tournaments/Batumi_op_2001/4111|publisher=365chess|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref>\n*2005: First place at [[Aeroflot Open]] section A2 Tournament;<ref>{{cite web|title=Moscow Aeroflot op-B 2005|url=https://www.365chess.com/tournaments/Moscow_Aeroflot_op-B_2005/33569|publisher=365chess|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref>\n*2005, 2006, 2007: First place at Armenian National Chess Championship. <ref>https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessplayer?pid=49431</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{citation |last=\u0549\u0561\u057f\u056b\u0576\u0575\u0561\u0576 |first=\u054c\u0561\u0586\u0561\u0575\u0565\u056c |year=1999 |title=\u0539\u0561\u0563\u0561\u056f\u056b\u0580\u0576\u0565\u0580\u0568 (1934-1998 \u0569\u0569.) |page=95 |publisher= |language=Armenian |isbn= }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{chessgames player|id=49431}}\n*[http://www.365chess.com/players/Arsen_Yegiazarian Arsen Yegiazarian] chess games at 365Chess.com\n*[http://www.redhotpawn.com/chess/grandmaster-games/index.php?player=Arsen_Yegiazarian&masterplayerid=1263 Grandmaster Games Database - Arsen Yegiazarian]\n*[http://www.olimpbase.org/players/tpltphti.html Olimpbase record] for Arsen Yegiazarian\n*[http://bbs.zixia.net/elite.php?file=%2Fgroups%2FEntertain%2Fchess%2Fsmthjh%2F5%2Fcontest%2F2004%2Ffourcountry%2F00000017.txt Interview with GM Arsen Yegiazarian]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090115021417/http://www.chessacademy.am/